  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  **PART 8 --- Reading Pipe Profiles & Calculating Depths**

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------

A pipe profile is a cross-sectional side view showing a pipe running
underground. It uses TWO different scales: one horizontal scale (matches
the plan view) and a VERTICAL scale that is exaggerated (typically 5x or
10x) to make slope visible.

**8.1 Key Profile Elements**

  ------------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Element**      **What to Read**   **How to Use It**
  ---------------- ------------------ ------------------------------------
  **Existing       Solid or dashed    Shows current grade before
  Ground Line      line at top        construction
  (EGL)**                             

  **Proposed Grade Solid line ---     Shows final finished grade after
  Line**           finished surface   construction
                   elevation          

  **Pipe           Line running       Shows pipe slope and grade
  Centerline**     through pipe       
                   center             

  **Invert         Number at each     Bottom inside of pipe --- used for
  Elevation (IE or structure          calculating cover depth
  INV)**                              

  **Rim Elevation  Number at top of   Top of manhole cover --- shows
  (RIM)**          manhole            finished grade here

  **Station        0+00, 1+00, 2+00   100-foot intervals. 2+50 = 250 feet
  Numbers**        etc.               from start.

  **Pipe Size &    Notation on pipe   e.g. \'8\" PVC SDR-35\' or \'12\"
  Material**       line               RCP Cl.III\'

  **Slope (S=)**   Noted as decimal   S=0.0050 = 0.50% slope. Always
                   or percent         verify adequate for velocity.

  **Vertical Scale In profile title   e.g. \'V. SCALE: 1\"=5\'\' ---
  Note**           block              different from H. scale!
  ------------------------------------------------------------------------

**8.2 Calculating Pipe Cover Depth from a Profile**

9.  Read the PROPOSED GRADE elevation at the pipe location (from top
    line of profile)

10. Read the pipe INVERT elevation at that same station

11. Add the pipe\'s outside diameter (OD) in feet to the invert
    elevation to get the TOP of pipe elevation

12. Cover depth = Proposed Grade elevation MINUS Top of Pipe elevation

*Example: Proposed grade = 105.50\'. Pipe invert = 101.20\'. 12\" RCP OD
= 1.08 ft. Top of pipe = 101.20 + 1.08 = 102.28\'. Cover = 105.50 -
102.28 = 3.22 ft. ✓ Exceeds 2 ft minimum.*

**8.3 Minimum Slope (Velocity) Requirements**

